What is the C# code to calculate the value of Planck's constant (h) and the energy of a photon with a wavelength of 600 nm, given the speed of light (c) as 299,792,458 m/s? Here is the table with the necessary variables:
|Variable | Symbol | Value |
|:-------:|:------:|:-----:|
|Wavelength of photon| λ | 600 nm|
|Speed of light | c | 299,792,458 m/s |
|Planck's constant | h | ? |
[C# code]
double wavelength = 600 * Math.Pow(10,-9); //convert nm to meters
double speedOfLight = 299792458;
double energy = (6.62607004 * Math.Pow(10,-34) * speedOfLight) / wavelength; //calculate energy using Planck's constant (h) and speed of light
double h = energy / speedOfLight;
Console.WriteLine("The value of Planck's constant (h) is: " + h.ToString() + " J s");
Console.WriteLine("The energy of a photon with a wavelength of 600 nm is: " + energy.ToString() + " J");

How can I improve the Python code for categorizing a list of flowers including Lilac, Daisy, Marigold, and Chrysanthemum using Java code? 
Here is a sample Java code that categorizes the flowers based on their names:
String[] flowers = {"Lilac", "Daisy", "Marigold", "Chrysanthemum"};
HashMap<String, ArrayList<String>> categories = new HashMap<String, ArrayList<String>>();
for (String flower : flowers) {
    String key = "";
    if (flower.startsWith("Li")) {
        key = "Lilac";
    } else if (flower.startsWith("Da")) {
        key = "Daisy";
    } else if (flower.startsWith("Ma")) {
        key = "Marigold";
    } else if (flower.startsWith("Ch")) {
        key = "Chrysanthemum";
    }
    if (categories.containsKey(key)) {
        categories.get(key).add(flower);
    } else {
        ArrayList<String> list = new ArrayList<String>();
        list.add(flower);
        categories.put(key, list);
    }
}
System.out.println(categories);
This code uses a HashMap to store the categories as keys and an ArrayList of flowers in each category as values. It also uses the startsWith method to check the first two letters of each flower's name.
